=========================================================
std::shared_ptr (C++11) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================================

1. What is std::shared_ptr?
---------------------------------------------------------
- std::shared_ptr is a smart pointer introduced in C++11.
- Provides SHARED ownership of a dynamically allocated object.
- Multiple shared_ptr objects can own the same resource.
- Uses reference counting to manage object lifetime.
- Object is destroyed automatically when reference count becomes 0.

Header:
#include <memory>

Syntax:
std::shared_ptr<int> p = std::make_shared<int>(10);

=========================================================
2. Why do we need shared_ptr?
---------------------------------------------------------
Problems with raw pointers:
- Manual delete required.
- Memory leaks.
- Double delete.
- Unclear ownership.

shared_ptr provides:
✔ Automatic memory management
✔ Shared ownership
✔ Exception safety
✔ RAII

=========================================================
3. RAII (VERY IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------------------
RAII:
Resource Acquisition Is Initialization.

Principle:
Acquire resource in constructor.
Release resource in destructor.

shared_ptr follows RAII:
- Acquires memory when created.
- Releases memory automatically.

=========================================================
4. Internal Working of shared_ptr (MOST ASKED)
---------------------------------------------------------
shared_ptr internally maintains:

1. Managed object pointer
2. Control Block

Control block stores:
- Strong reference count
- Weak reference count
- Custom deleter
- Allocator information

Diagram:

shared_ptr p1 ----\
                   \
shared_ptr p2 ------> Control Block
                   /     ref_count = 2
shared_ptr p3 ----/      weak_count = 0
                         |
                         v
                      Object

=========================================================
5. Reference Counting
---------------------------------------------------------
Example:

auto p1 = make_shared<int>(10);

Count = 1

auto p2 = p1;

Count = 2

auto p3 = p2;

Count = 3

When p3 goes out of scope:

Count = 2

When p2 goes out of scope:

Count = 1

When p1 goes out of scope:

Count = 0

Object deleted automatically.

=========================================================
6. use_count()
---------------------------------------------------------
Returns number of shared owners.

Example:

auto p1 = make_shared<int>(10);

cout << p1.use_count();

Output:
1

auto p2 = p1;

cout << p1.use_count();

Output:
2

Complexity:
O(1)

Interview:
Avoid using use_count() for program logic in multithreaded code.

=========================================================
7. Example
---------------------------------------------------------

shared_ptr<int> p1 = make_shared<int>(100);

shared_ptr<int> p2 = p1;

cout << p1.use_count();

Output:
2

=========================================================
8. Copy Constructor
---------------------------------------------------------

shared_ptr<int> p1 = make_shared<int>(10);

shared_ptr<int> p2(p1);

Reference count:

1 → 2

No object copy occurs.

Only:
- pointer copied
- reference count incremented

Complexity:
O(1)

=========================================================
9. Copy Assignment
---------------------------------------------------------

shared_ptr<int> p1 = make_shared<int>(10);
shared_ptr<int> p2;

p2 = p1;

Count:

1 → 2

Complexity:
O(1)

=========================================================
10. Move Constructor
---------------------------------------------------------

shared_ptr<int> p1 = make_shared<int>(10);

shared_ptr<int> p2(std::move(p1));

After move:

p1 == nullptr
p2 owns object

Reference count remains:

1

No increment/decrement.

Complexity:
O(1)

=========================================================
11. Move Assignment
---------------------------------------------------------

shared_ptr<int> p1 = make_shared<int>(10);
shared_ptr<int> p2;

p2 = std::move(p1);

After move:

p1 == nullptr
p2 owns object

Count remains:

1

=========================================================
12. reset()
---------------------------------------------------------
Releases ownership.

Example:

auto p = make_shared<int>(10);

p.reset();

Count becomes:

0

Object deleted.

Can also replace object:

p.reset(new int(50));

=========================================================
13. get()
---------------------------------------------------------
Returns raw pointer.

Example:

auto p = make_shared<int>(10);

int* ptr = p.get();

Never:

delete ptr;

Because shared_ptr will delete it.

=========================================================
14. swap()
---------------------------------------------------------

auto p1 = make_shared<int>(10);
auto p2 = make_shared<int>(20);

p1.swap(p2);

Objects exchanged.

Complexity:
O(1)

=========================================================
15. unique()
---------------------------------------------------------

auto p = make_shared<int>(10);

p.unique();

Returns:

true

After:

auto p2 = p;

p.unique();

Returns:

false

Note:
unique() removed in C++20.

=========================================================
16. Custom Deleter (IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------------------

auto deleter =
[](int* p)
{
    cout << "Deleting\n";
    delete p;
};

shared_ptr<int> p(new int(10), deleter);

Use cases:
- FILE*
- sockets
- database handles
- OS resources

=========================================================
17. make_shared() (VERY IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------------------

auto p = make_shared<int>(10);

Advantages:

✔ Faster
✔ Exception safe
✔ Single memory allocation
✔ Better cache locality

=========================================================
18. Without make_shared()
---------------------------------------------------------

shared_ptr<int> p(new int(10));

Memory:

Allocation #1:
Object

Allocation #2:
Control block

Two allocations.

=========================================================
19. With make_shared()
---------------------------------------------------------

auto p = make_shared<int>(10);

Memory:

Single allocation:
---------------------
Control block
Object
---------------------

Advantages:
- fewer allocations
- better performance
- better cache locality

=========================================================
20. Why prefer make_shared over new? (MOST ASKED)
---------------------------------------------------------

shared_ptr<int> p(new int(10));

Two allocations.

make_shared:

auto p = make_shared<int>(10);

One allocation.

Advantages:
- Faster
- Exception safe
- Less fragmentation
- Better cache locality

=========================================================
21. Thread Safety (MOST ASKED)
---------------------------------------------------------

Reference count manipulation is thread-safe.

This is safe:

shared_ptr<int> p1 = make_shared<int>(10);
shared_ptr<int> p2 = p1;

Reference count update:
Atomic.

BUT:

Object itself is NOT thread-safe.

Example:

shared_ptr<vector<int>> p;

p->push_back(10);

Multiple threads:
Need mutex.

Interview line:

shared_ptr's control block is thread-safe;
managed object is not.

=========================================================
22. Circular Dependency Problem (VERY IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------------------

class B;

class A
{
public:
    shared_ptr<B> bptr;
};

class B
{
public:
    shared_ptr<A> aptr;
};

auto a = make_shared<A>();
auto b = make_shared<B>();

a->bptr = b;
b->aptr = a;

Counts:

A = 2
B = 2

Both counts never become 0.

Memory leak.

=========================================================
23. Solution: weak_ptr
---------------------------------------------------------

class B;

class A
{
public:
    shared_ptr<B> bptr;
};

class B
{
public:
    weak_ptr<A> aptr;
};

weak_ptr:
- Non-owning reference
- Does not increase reference count
- Breaks cyclic dependency

=========================================================
24. enable_shared_from_this (IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------------------

Allows object to safely create shared_ptr to itself.

class A :
public enable_shared_from_this<A>
{
public:
    shared_ptr<A> getPtr()
    {
        return shared_from_this();
    }
};

Without this:

shared_ptr<A>(this);

Can create multiple control blocks.

Double delete.

=========================================================
25. Aliasing Constructor (Senior Level)
---------------------------------------------------------

auto p1 = make_shared<vector<int>>(10);

shared_ptr<int> p2(p1, &(*p1)[0]);

p2 shares ownership with p1
but points to first element.

=========================================================
26. Performance
---------------------------------------------------------

Copy:
O(1)

Assignment:
O(1)

Move:
O(1)

Reference count update:
Atomic operations

More expensive than:
unique_ptr

=========================================================
27. shared_ptr vs unique_ptr
---------------------------------------------------------

unique_ptr
-----------
Single owner
No reference count
Fastest
Cannot copy
Can move

shared_ptr
-----------
Multiple owners
Reference count
More overhead
Can copy
Can move

